An intense struggle at the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you on how to choose
While virtually all mobiles know how to read MP3 files, no MP3 drives know to call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only one phone.
There are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end cheap grimophone to put the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
If there are vinyl discs in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a grimophone.
The same applies to music during travel, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories depending on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns for a reader, the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would have trouble supporting listeners bought for twenty crowns in the market.
There are two extremes, among which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is broad.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than simply playing music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Besides the primary functions, phone calls and text messages, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a variable quality camera and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge can grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically seeing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The greater the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between the two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy bowls.
There are few mobiles who are able to read music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this number is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the rudimentary music players) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you can call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second reload for the work - this being valid even for the more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players who are capable of continuous operation for at least 9 hours, including the least performing, following reloading.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be connected directly to the computer, without any special software.
Of course, you can save music directly on the memory card, but few card players know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need, except for the iPod, any software.
Just fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the interpreter, the title of the album, the style, or then the judgement of the user.
Some devices only display an index with tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iliver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, be particularly interested in the battery life, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you will only have any mobile reading the MP3.
Almost all mobiles are able to do so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
Everyone can read the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will precisely have this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of the devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Just visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or of another supplier) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for acquiring a musical mobile.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and, in most cases, is limited to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (either by GSM, the Internet or the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobility on their own.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get out of your pocket's mobile, while you forgot your MP3 drive at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use built-in enclosures, which almost all mobile devices have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical movements is their price.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases you will be limited by the absence of exit for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best tools, also equipped with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone can order the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest ones (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or of a Gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a random connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose from
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (M2, microSD type, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models usually support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get rid of it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you must not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose more specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the control ease approaches that of an independent MP3 drive.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 drives sold separately, is the one that went the longest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 drive produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missed for a long time.
We have already mentioned on many occasions on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Agency (ČTū), which said that the price of a text message was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of the Czech mobile operators cheaper than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this respect, Pavel Dvo the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who repeatedly stated that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with his own network apparently has only a lot of luck (there would be only a few frequencies now).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a significant fall in prices, which was subsequently to be responded to by traditional operators.
However, before even the market entry of the hordes such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those heard at home today were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual Mobilking operator.
In only six months, this operator has managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and become the country's fifth operator.
In addition, behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which includes the Czech U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a traditional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages, which is often offset by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers at least twice as much SMS as its competitors in Britain.
However, as illustrated by Mobilking's example in Poland, relying on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator that they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept could also work with us.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman for Vodafone, in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which is based most virtual operators.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project successfully, but negotiations in the Czech Republic are not very encouraging.
Mobilking's launch will take place rather in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic were not in any way in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer sector, has not, for a long time, hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We want much to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner will be the better.
We have already had negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
Together with some, we managed to make progress in the negotiations," said the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl group.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we might already be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not estimate that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the time being, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Srše the Press Department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Spokesperson Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not registered for the moment a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate within such a limited time frame, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to the completion of the requests for his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared charges and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the customers' perspective.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile Internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a fall in prices and therefore a fall in profits.
What is the point of facilitating the emergence of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to agree as if they were going to show. Chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTū, during the creation of the U:fon, was that exercised by T-Mobile.
Evidence of this is evidence of publicly available information from the ČTū web pages.
Now, today, the U:fon is willing to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition on the mobile market has also been recently amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disappointing.
However, it is not just the attitude of the ČTū, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (EYOHS).
However, the latter adopted its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has not been of sufficient interest to conventional operators in the past," said Kristián Chapoplo in response to our question from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
A statement made in this way would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a declaration is more than misleading.
Especially since Kristián Chapau added: "Where virtual operators are normally present abroad, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a fall in prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure towards an honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices appear not to be part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which derives from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the random and hard fight against competition.
"The Office did not find signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore none of them has an increased corresponding responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools necessary for the opening of the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecoms regulator," said Chaloupa.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTū, according to which telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts have a different view: in order for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must always be obtained.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
Thus he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least of concern to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are doing so in a similar way.
However, complaints from many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Relapsing responsibility on the ČTū is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes hands of the case.
We have already met this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to bring about the innovation of the Telecommunications Act, recently adopted, an expansion of the powers of the ČTū in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This is something the representatives of the OOHS must know very well, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When nobody looks, it can work
However, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators, several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, there are firms involved in multi-level marketing.
Special mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms generally only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic business client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it receives special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are talking about were to happen, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would consider, which could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question on this problem, Martina Kemrová.
However, it is unlikely that such an activity would not have reached the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
However, the operator does not take a decision against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring significant benefits, and at the same time, contrary to the real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators."
That is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTū.
In addition, there is another question to ask at the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to reveal such an activity, and if it does not wish to confine itself to the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the dearest country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a significant fall in the price of services.
However, almost in all the countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators tried, sometimes more or less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies in the developed countries have intervened, which did not defend the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Both through formal measures and through informal pressure, they eventually got the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory agencies deal with this issue in the form of a hot potato that is released by passing it on to a near target.
As a result of our experience, we can only get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But don't throw the handle after the cog.
If the background information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear, the Czech mobile market may be moving.
If one operator has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will be difficult to maintain in the face of the rejection (to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The hymn was once again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Ji the Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kn theková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremi, Jaroslav Krček, is the author of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to the Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the interpretation of the solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"Since the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, have a good saying, so that we understand the words well, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
Kde domov můj recorded for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (The Theatre of States) in Fidlovacka (Kermesse des savetiers), Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škrup.
It became popular and people spontaneously adapted it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couple naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
He remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
