Pragic public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
On Wednesday 1st October 2008 will be recorded in the history of Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transportation Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will go up in the metro, trams and buses, who instead of having a paper ticket, will have in their pocket an electronic coupon.
At the moment, the card is available for about 100 thousand people, owners of the Opencard chip card.
Passengers may buy a coupon of 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have it registered on their smart card in the information points and offices of Dopravní podnik (the Transportation Agency), located in the metro stations of Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra the Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Latviany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday there is also the possibility of buying coupons via internet on the Dopravní podnik web pages: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people benefited from the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store can permanently forget the windows in metro stations, where they have so far had to walk impatiently in long tails in order to obtain paper tickets.
In fact, they will buy their coupon via internet and they will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these points of contact, there is at the disposal of passengers a window with trained personnel, which will help the interested parties with the purchase by internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they bought on their card," says the spokesperson of the Martin Opatrný project.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to record electronic coupons on the Opencard in automatic distributors installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminding the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
An automaton will check the coupon instead of the driver
The machines that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and the coupon previously purchased will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surroundings of the city.
It is known in the peri-urban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which mainly use the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia to access the capital.
