The Sudetes were calling for a referendum in the United States
In 1945, the Germans of the South demanded that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This follows from a letter filed in the collections of Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Southern Bohemian Scientific Library).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of South African Germans were allegedly addressed to the President of the United States with such a desire.
This derives, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
In the letter, Germans from Český Krumlov asked the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have well understood the situation and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that the American troops come on German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Šumava is at heart".
Since the rally in Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only with brutality, unrespectable attitudes, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter pray the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of the Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppressed and destroyed minorities and which in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of millions of inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech Oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetes of the time.
While the Czech Germans had at least to realize that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them had such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to gain some form of autonomy for the South.
Others thought they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chapau, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When, at the end of the war, he was captured by the English and placed in the Holstein capture camp, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to learn Czech.
"They thought that once they returned home, the Czech Republic would benefit them," said Chapau.
According to him, none of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
