Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cafard flees from danger, does that mean he also feels afraid?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we check that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe the animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that the other human beings have a consciousness.
But in that case, at least it can be hoped that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or general consciousness, we enter hard-to-work terrain because the Hardware does not correspond.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he kills, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists draw a comparable subjective experience from it.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our experience subjective to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated with the human consciousness almost always include the pre-frontal side cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in management and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be completely absent from other beings.
At least for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the pre-frontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is different even from the other primates.
Another significant characteristic could be the linguistic nature of man: much of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, whatever its way of being produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is so difficult to determine what other animals may be aware of.
If this, internal and subjective, does not allow itself to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyze based on our own experience, then its observation poses us with major problems.
