German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some productions with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes over the particular iconography of the flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the public.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a unique character.
What I was interested in was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the personality moments of the flamenco stars ".
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a flat camera.
They are portraits that, thanks to the choice of the camera and the equipment, evokes classical photography.
The implementation of various stylistic means breaks down with the classic side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of the flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
This is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captures the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic has been the constant of this work presented today at the El Fotómata Gallery.
The flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
