The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcoholosis, to have a system in his vehicle that prevents the vehicle from starting in a state of drunkness, or if he does not breathe.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now reflected in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last for one year.
Its aim is the rehabilitation of the driver by offering road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State responsible for road safety, as well as the Directorate General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety Foundation, will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a drunk state, the car resumes.
Alcolock would avoid this, since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the throat and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's rate of alcohol is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is more than EUR 1,000 and is borne by the driver.
In this regard, a 2007 study in the United States showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced the offences by up to 65% during the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 people each year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, but criminal reform requires a reform of the organic law.
The scheme is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one for experimental use.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Members will vote an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party that proposes to install in school buses this system as it has been done in France.
