Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake by telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens can surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It is a blessed change in sleep called sleepiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who talks during the night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadicly (for example, once in life associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other changes in sleep such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (pipi in bed) or somnambulism, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very strong fever, stress or overexcitement.
In any case, this is a little researched phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with screams, tears, long speeches ...
In the event that sleepiness becomes very common, it would be appropriate to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check whether there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for the problem.
We have said that this is a blessed alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another change in sleep that can be treated (e.g., if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, seek quiet games and avoid more or less violent television programs or series.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if he is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not try to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because by sleeping, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so you pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interview him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even kidding.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
