Interview - Blood back safe
Hema-Québec was celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to be happy because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence, which had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the grailness of the public, the Government of Canada launched in February 1994 a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to cease to occur.
While Judge Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan for a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, only 38% of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work in the field during the following years have been made to regain public confidence," she proudly stated, saying that, at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
From its creation on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, were being reported in Europe, which has held the strength since its foundation in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when one does not know it and a serious disease can result from it, namely Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by the degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures were introduced.
As a result, in April 1999, the blood of people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
However, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted by blood.
This episode has shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied makes sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing emerged on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs) which allow the presence of the virus itself in donor blood to be detected directly and not that of antibodies to the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs were able to shorten the mute period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
This significantly reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowledge and that they will not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, 1 in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, this will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that it is now convenient to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover from health," says Hema-Québec's Chief Executive Officer.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than last year appeared on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"Requirements are increasing because the population is ageing.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often require recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences on the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
However, any healthy person, aged 18 and over, who meets the eligibility criteria, can give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is present, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this network of donors as they age and can no longer give their blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and to encourage them to become a regular donor.
Since today's life is so horrified, there is rarely time to spend an hour giving her blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood from stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and plans to take more than a thousand of them annually.
We should start by proposing these for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it," Hema-Québec is unable to offer this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals in Quebec.
