Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-President of the Canadian Barrick Gold Mine.
In pursuit of a Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world's largest aurior company has initiated a defamation charge of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without the need for the aim of launching a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to the ruin of anyone who dares to support a position contrary to their own?
No matter what the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defences and to fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers backed by pockets almost without a bottom of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is also often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will shatter the opposition as well as scare anyone who dares to look at the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was in public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are usually through the exchange of ideas and not through battling.
It was therefore sufficient to open his books, his files and establish a real debate through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust the public and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public.
In the Vice-President's world, it seems that this word refers only to the fatly paid lawyers, not all Canadians; that's a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What doesn't - or doesn't want to - Barrick Gold is that the public supports Black Canada's authors and publishers because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to hear and judge Barrick, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, not in the context of what several people perceive as a prosecution (as a result of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed an appeal against the authors of Black Canada asking them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreptitious speech, Barrick Gold's pursuit is a direct attack on freedom of university research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in a block, the right to quote credible sources and the debate on facts and interpretations, which constitute the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that bother the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under repeated prosecution, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has the right to reply.
The academic community to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time governments put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, have finally reached an agreement yesterday on the greatest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months is still to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, for new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, for new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default of payment, and for a right to look at the wages paid to the managers of the assisted enterprises.
The U.S. Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, after a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush Administration representative Henry Paulson.
"All has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis in Wall Street," explained the democrat.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not, trauma, chaos and disturbances on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned to a sprint in the last few hours, fearing the effect of a new failure on the mood of investors.
The deadline was the opening of the markets this morning.
Together with the negotiations late, the two candidates for the US presidential election were more in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfied that it was necessary to reach this end.
Senator Democrat Barack Obama has attributed to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the provision to allow owners to keep their homes and the provision on the salary of government-backed business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no welcome.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the American television waves.
Asked if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of not doing anything is simply not acceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan is designed to buy with taxpayers' money the suspicious, risky and insellable debts of US financial institutions.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (ACCPs) and leading to a freeze of liquidity and to the unbundling of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who had the first draft agreement capped last week.
It is believed to be out of this deadlock since the Democrats have accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round out the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government were to assume losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover.
The new plan provides for the first instalment of 250 billion, to be added to 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
Another 350 billion is expected to be approved by another Congress vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will receive shares in the saved companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment is over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the housing seizure procedures for real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as setting limits on compensation and departure payments to managers of affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see him put to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to the House of Representatives on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green fire.
Indeed, votes continued yesterday against this project, both in the Republican camp and in the Democratic Party.
"Of course, Washington does not hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that consists of taking advantage of taxpayers".
The leader of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", the Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred prominent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prizes, have written to us, saying that the Congress is being asked not to press ahead and to carefully examine the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe once again demonstrated the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three countries of the Benélux announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had not acquired its competitor in the cold since it lost EUR 2 billion (US 2.9 billion) in the US crisis of risky real estate loans.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos.
In exchange, there is a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It's just something that savers and households now appreciate that times are coming up uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalising another bank that was misguided by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take back on its behalf all current loans to the Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
