The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
In auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overestimate the commodity.
New York University's neurology and economics researchers have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this well-known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in Science magazine, human beings do not want to be dissociated during this type of competition, such as auctioning on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
These researches have attempted to create a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" by means of sales at experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played the loto, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (IRMf) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction of which an essential element is the over-sell of a third party, the whole under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensively when the part was lost.
This part of the brain, in addition to several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
That is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial oversight analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overburdening a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the group about the actual value of the product in question, and they did so.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would receive an additional $15, in reward.
While the third group received the $15 prior to the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auctions.
The difference between these two groups is, in fact, that the emphasis was on victory, while the emphasis was on failure.
By proving the hypothesis of the neurologists, the players' team "against the failure" were prepared for higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any economic theory that already exists.
In fact, each of them explained the phenomena observed at auctions only by the pleasure of winning and setting it at risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by leading, now, to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned among the first causes of death.
It is estimated that one hundred miles of patients carrying the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles follow a treatment. This is because often the patients do not know that they are carrying the virus.
The hepatitis name is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and the diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogen genes, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tube (e.g. food or water contaminated), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, vaccination against viruses A and B is recommended anyway. There is no C vaccine.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, generally accompanied by general poor condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then there is a visible yellowish on the skin and on the white of the eye, the legs become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogenic gene will gently destroy the liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as is regular testing.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently there are 200 million patients with C-type chronic hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contamination disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30th is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development, and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a kind of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph has published an article that researchers from the University of Oxford have carried out an interesting experience by analysing how much faith in God could influence tolerance to the pain of the human being.
As part of this least strange experience, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electrochocs, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it has also been discovered that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiences in which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument that sparks sparks and spreads the electrochocs is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look steadily at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady at the Hermine painted by Léonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the vision of the Virgin Mary would evoke a sort of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was about its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, 20 electrochocs were received in four parts succeeding, while looking either at the painting with religious theme or the painting with more general theme.
The Catholics said that, in the view of the Virgin Mary, they felt like "safe," like someone who is "careed" and they "rested, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in the atheists, provided that one finds the right photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican Bishop, praised the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and, in many cases, actually change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, it is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows the believers a Madonna painted by Léonard or by a painter of the same size?
Would the view of a better quality Virgin Mary produce better results?
