The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bourdon
What better method would be used to develop suitable technologies to avoid an obstacle, unless it is the imitation of an existing obstacle detector already in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, which takes place in Japan, the bees gave the strategic idea of starting with the engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robotic car, a bio-inspired self-robotized system of BR23C type, which he has equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During his flights, each bee forms its own oval-shaped space, which in reality resembles our secure protective shell - explained, at the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the department of research and development and the brand's public technological relations.
The face-to-face bee eye plays a vital role, as it is capable of seeing in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-to-face eye, the engineers addressed the idea of laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movement of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it from a sufficient angle to avoid the collision.
Contrary to any current system, this avoidance manoeuvre takes place entirely instinctively.
"If this was not the case, the mini auto robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Laboratoire Mobility and robotized car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference can not go up, down or in diagonal, it can be only two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid the other bees, in our case, only the rotating movement, acceleration and slowing as manoeuvres available to the mini auto robot could be used.
BR23C uses lighter, lighter lithium-polymer batteries with a higher energy concentration, making their life span longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should only address and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of the previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a giga-byte capacity, or even mega-byte capacity.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. Nissan estimates that this system will enter series-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
