Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent from the previous month, and 12.9 per cent from the month of August 2007 - communicates to the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared with one year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry were only slightly higher by 0.1 per cent than in July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear goods manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first of all the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6 per cent).
The result was a deflation in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), machinery and electrical equipment manufacturing (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
The other industries in the processing industry experienced an increase of 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the sectors of supply of electricity, gas, steam and water, representing a significant weight in the national industrial operation, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in the price of gas introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector have experienced the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgy sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important food, beverage and tobacco sector, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, the price increase has changed between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
In the whole processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 per cent in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and sector breakdowns, in August, it was investment-based profit-making sectors that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In consumer goods production, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while in energy and material producing sectors for further processing there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for subsequent transformation (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-making sectors, it was reduced by 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment means declined by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
