Mp3 player pointed to the finger, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to full volume music for a prolonged period of time using portable musical instruments such as Mp3 players can cause permanent damage to the hearing.
This is what the European Commission has announced, which, in a communiqué published in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the recently identified and unforeseen health risks (Csrseri) of the EU published today.
"of this scientific report-read us in the note- it turns out that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable musical instruments, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data - pursues the responsible Ue- it is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow new technologies"
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical instruments and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"The scientists-concluded executive confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be adopted to better protect children and adolescents against noise exposure from portable and similar musical instruments.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100Db, but concern is increasing about hearing damage that might result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to effectively limit these data using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to music in full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those listening to music under such conditions for prolonged periods are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to about 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
