The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already appeared a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the rescue plan of $700 billion approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times yesterday that confirms it to us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more shared between its cautious East Coast soul, favouring federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washingtons" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, which was made to feel despotic with the vote I was talking to you about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just an example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake is predicting or is already making: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and can be not only here.
In the United States as well as in Europe, the crisis seems to have accelerated the phenomena that have been covered in recent times, to the point that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and manifesting themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-updating, extraordinary revival, of the dual category of sovereign state, compared to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with foreign countries, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it is governed: that is to say, to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically, it is almost national.
Political internationalisation does not seem to be at stake, nor does it have much to say: the obvious proof is provided by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, fails to decide any common policy line.
And so, it is the government of each state that everyone is waiting for intervention, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a provision of credits: when we go through a difficult period, there is only the States that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things in place.
They also have the means and legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements of which neither a market nor an international organization can ever have in a similar way.
This new phase of the state-nation crisis is also in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that the more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor that is quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, when we were convinced that we have now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at once that our future will have to deal more and more with rather less material things such as water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but are absolutely connected to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more maps than he who is not, that is, he who has the evil chance of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now arrive at the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably said Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis appears to produce two convergent phenomena.
On one side, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discretion for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadows.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inappropriateness, a sense of distance that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far to their apogee, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have at the same time, and to be always more alien to the opinions of the majority.
In short, the demand for leadership, fuelled in an underground way, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised "revolts" of elections or indeed, in the changes of collective moods of recent times, from the conservative ascent in Bavaria Austria, to the fall of the workers in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressists against Bush (and it might well be that the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, would say someone, have more and more difficulty, which does not date from today, to understand and thus to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and agitates potentially disproportionately.
In view of all this, speaking of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But it's said well, keep your eyes wide open, it's not without reason.
