Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market does not know of a crisis
According to the Sunia's latest survey, the tenant's union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects in order to exclude entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to support- explains the head of Sunia's study office, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the strong demand from students has distorted the market so much that a general increase process has begun for the residents themselves.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered contracts, without rent limit, sub-rents.
For Sunia, extraordinary intervention through the revision of the tax is necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from a minimum of 650 euros (the Bande Nere zone), to an average of 800 euros (the Lambite zone, the Udine zone, and the Fiera zone) to a maximum of 900 euros (the Vittoria zone)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, 250/280 euros are required for a double bed, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are requested for a single, 450 for a double bed.
Smallly lower values (550 euros for a simple) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save money if you travel in peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 euros for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, expenditure from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vandero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are in absolute terms lower, but they are of major importance in the city economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rents are often taken by extra-Community students, have a subsequent anomaly: the rent requested to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Good-bye old Paradiso cinema, the cities elect the historic halls.
The historic cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the large multi-rooms, and the death of consummation of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inextricable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historical places loaded with memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a bit of the road and so many emotions," observes the director of Nuovo Paradiso cinema, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the juror of Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial room, and nostalgia in a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and these are the halls of the main cities that paid mainly for them: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, the Emilie Romaine is in the lead with 82 single-room cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-salt cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has developed in an irrational way" observed Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those who already exist, because when a room is closed in a city, these visitors are not necessarily all willing to go to the multiplex.
Not to mention the missing debate on credit for traders: the government's past debt is about EUR 10 million.
It is a shame that, from a ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million per year would be needed.
We note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, concerned with these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the mono-room cinemas of the historical centres and on the outskirts.
Among the normative measures, there are measures of tax relief for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators can enter the limited traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
"It's an initiative that pleases me," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna setting up other measures.
It is clear, however, that in contrast to the superpower of multiplex, traditional rooms must also improve the sound and image quality, as today's public is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradiso cinema" which I thought for ten years already.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn from the other side not to see the blackboards through the dust.
